European Explorers of the New World: Exploration of explorers who ventured into the New World during the Age of Exploration,

Cleopatra VII: The last active ruler of the Ptolemaic Kingdom of Egypt, known for her intelligence, charisma, and relationships with Julius Caesar and Mark Antony.

Alexander the Great: Macedonian king and military commander who created one of the largest empires in history, stretching from Greece to Egypt and India.

Joan of Arc: French heroine and military leader who played a pivotal role in the Hundred Years' War, leading French forces to victory at the Siege of Orléans.

Napoleon Bonaparte: French military and political leader who rose to prominence during the French Revolution and became Emperor of the French, known for his military conquests and legal reforms.

Queen Elizabeth I: Queen of England and Ireland known for her long and prosperous reign, which saw the defeat of the Spanish Armada and the flourishing of English literature and exploration.

Genghis Khan: Founder and Great Khan of the Mongol Empire, one of the largest contiguous land empires in history, known for his military tactics and cultural influence.

Leonardo da Vinci: Italian polymath known for his expertise in various fields, including painting, sculpting, architecture, science, mathematics, engineering, and invention.

Christopher Columbus: Italian explorer who completed four voyages across the Atlantic Ocean, leading to widespread European awareness of the Americas and initiating the Age of Exploration.

Martin Luther: German monk and theologian who initiated the Protestant Reformation, challenging the authority of the Catholic Church and sparking religious and social change across Europe.

Mahatma Gandhi: Indian lawyer, anti-colonial nationalist, and political ethicist who led India to independence through nonviolent civil disobedience, inspiring movements for civil rights and freedom worldwide.

Winston Churchill: British statesman and Prime Minister during World War II, known for his leadership during the Blitz and his inspirational speeches rallying the British people.

Queen Victoria: Queen of the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland, whose reign saw the expansion of the British Empire and significant social, political, and cultural changes in Britain.

Abraham Lincoln: 16th President of the United States, who led the country through the Civil War, preserved the Union, and issued the Emancipation Proclamation, ending slavery in the Confederate states.

Elizabeth Cady Stanton: American suffragist, social activist, and leading figure of the early women's rights movement, who played a pivotal role in organizing the Seneca Falls Convention and drafting the Declaration of Sentiments.

Sir Isaac Newton: English mathematician, physicist, and astronomer, who formulated the laws of motion and universal gravitation, laying the groundwork for classical mechanics and modern physics.

Mansa Musa: Emperor of the Mali Empire, who is considered one of the wealthiest individuals in history due to his vast fortune and extravagant pilgrimage to Mecca, which brought attention to West Africa and its wealth.

Hatshepsut: Fifth pharaoh of the Eighteenth Dynasty of Egypt, who ruled as a regent for her stepson, Thutmose III, and later declared herself pharaoh, becoming one of the most successful pharaohs of ancient Egypt.

Attila the Hun: Ruler of the Huns who led invasions of the Roman Empire, earning a reputation as a fearsome and ruthless conqueror, known as the "Scourge of God."

Marco Polo: Venetian merchant, explorer, and writer who traveled to Asia along the Silk Road and served as an emissary for the Mongol Empire, documenting his experiences in "The Travels of Marco Polo."

Galileo Galilei: Italian astronomer, physicist, and mathematician, who made significant contributions to the scientific revolution, including improvements to the telescope and observations supporting the heliocentric model of the solar system.

Ramses II: Third pharaoh of the Nineteenth Dynasty of Egypt, who is often regarded as one of the greatest and most powerful pharaohs in Egyptian history, known for his military campaigns and monumental building projects.

Catherine the Great: Empress of Russia, whose reign saw the expansion of the Russian Empire, modernization of its administration, and cultural flourishing known as the Russian Enlightenment.

Homer: Ancient Greek poet traditionally said to be the author of the epic poems "The Iliad" and "The Odyssey," which are foundational works of Western literature and mythology.

Voltaire: French Enlightenment writer, philosopher, and advocate for freedom of speech and religious tolerance, whose works include "Candide" and numerous essays and letters advocating for social and political reform.

Julius Caesar: Roman general, statesman, and dictator who played a critical role in the events that led to the demise of the Roman Republic and the rise of the Roman Empire.

Marie Antoinette: Queen of France and wife of Louis XVI, whose lavish lifestyle and perceived indifference to the plight of the French people contributed to public resentment and the French Revolution.

Socrates: Classical Greek philosopher credited as one of the founders of Western philosophy, known for his contributions to ethics, epistemology, and dialectics, as well as his method of questioning known as the Socratic method.

Cleopatra: Last active ruler of the Ptolemaic Kingdom of Egypt, known for her relationships with Julius Caesar and Mark Antony, and her role in the political intrigue of the Roman Republic.

Michelangelo: Italian Renaissance artist renowned for his contributions to painting, sculpture, and architecture, including masterpieces such as the Sistine Chapel ceiling and the statue of David.

William Shakespeare: English playwright and poet widely regarded as the greatest writer in the English language and the world's preeminent dramatist, whose works include "Hamlet," "Romeo and Juliet," and "Macbeth."

Benjamin Franklin: American polymath and Founding Father of the United States, known for his contributions to science, invention, diplomacy, and the American Revolution.

Nelson Mandela: South African anti-apartheid revolutionary and political leader who served as President of South Africa from 1994 to 1999, known for his role in ending apartheid and promoting reconciliation and peace.

Florence Nightingale: British social reformer and founder of modern nursing, known for her pioneering work during the Crimean War and her efforts to improve healthcare and sanitation standards.

Thomas Jefferson: Third President of the United States and principal author of the Declaration of Independence, known for his advocacy of liberty, democracy, and individual rights.

Gautama Buddha: Founder of Buddhism, whose teachings and principles have had a profound impact on religious and philosophical thought in Asia and around the world.

Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart: Austrian composer and prodigy who created a prolific body of work, including symphonies, operas, chamber music, and concertos, despite his tragically short life.

Gandhi: Indian lawyer, anti-colonial nationalist, and political ethicist who led India to independence through nonviolent civil disobedience, inspiring movements for civil rights and freedom worldwide.
